    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The State vs. the Press</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Norman Schorr (Overseas Press Club of America) on Sept 5 editorial cites other examples of government efforts to silence independent press</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Many other examples can be added to your Sept. 5 editorial about the epidemic of government attempts to silence independent journalists.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Many other examples can be added to your Sept. 5 editorial about the epidemic of government attempts to silence independent journalists.</p>
        <p>One example is Russia, where President Vladimir V. Putin has stated that press freedom is ''an unshakable value of Russian democracy.'' Yet he has regularly used his powers to intimidate the media, most notably in the jailing of Vladimir A. Gusinsky, chairman of the Media-Most news organization.</p>
        <p>Another is Cambodia, where Prime Minister Hun Sen has publicly acknowledged the benefits of an unfettered media. Yet he suspended publication of the newspaper Cambodia News Bulletin after an article on royal succession was said to be in violation of the Constitution, which states that the Cambodian king ''shall be inviolable.''</p>
        <p>NORMAN SCHORR  New York, Sept. 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is co-chairman of the Freedom of the Press Committee of the Overseas Press Club of America.</p>
      </block>
